Introduction to Spring Boot
---------------------------
Spring Boot is an open-source Java-based framework used to create stand-alone, production-ready applications quickly and easily. It is built on top of the Spring Framework and reduces the complexity of Java development by providing auto-configuration, embedded servers, and ready-to-use features.

Spring Boot helps developers build web applications, REST APIs, microservices, and enterprise applications with minimal configuration. It follows the convention-over-configuration approach, which means developers can focus more on business logic instead of complex setup.

Key Features of Spring Boot
Auto Configuration
Embedded Servers (Tomcat, Jetty)
Faster Development
Production-ready Features
Microservices Support
Easy Dependency Management
Advantages
Reduces boilerplate code
Simplifies project setup
Easy integration with databases and APIs
Suitable for enterprise-level applications
Supports rapid application development

Spring Boot is widely used in modern software development because it makes Java application development faster, simpler, and more efficient.
